entry.title: Introduce kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp feature
entry.content:
This CL introduces kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp

feature. kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp keeps track of anchor tag, and

warms up the relevant service workers in the following timings.



- If sw_warm_up_on_visible is true, and when the anchor becomes visible.

- if sw_warm_up_on_pointerover is true, and when the mouse hovers on the anchor.

- if sw_warm_up_on_pointerdown is true, and when the mouse button is pressed on the anchor.



sw_warm_up_max_count feature param controls the maximum number of

service workers that is warmed-up.



Not to prevent navigation and loading, kSpeculativeServiceWorkerWarmUp

waits for onload. After onload, the accumulated URLs are sent to the

browser process, and will be processed to warm up service workers. After

onload, If any events that can warm up service workers happen, these URL

candidates will be sent to the browser process immediately.







This CL adds AnchorElementObserverForServiceWorker class. This class

observes the following events.



- anchor becomes visible

- pointer over

- pointer down

- onload



AnchorElementObserverForServiceWorker gathers URLs, and send them to the

browser process by using

MaybeStartOutermostMainFrameNavigation().



In the browser side,

RenderFrameHostImpl::MaybeStartOutermostMainFrameNavigation

receives URL candidates, and passes it to WarmUpServiceWorker()

function. WarmUpServiceWorker() function stores the request into

ServiceWorkerContextCore.



ServiceWorkerContextWrapper warms up a service worker if there is a

remaining warm-up request. This process is done one-by-one in

serial. MaybeProcessPendingWarmUpRequest() function does this serial

warm-up operation recursively.

entry.title: [remoting] Fix host crash when receiving target_framerate message.
entry.content:
The MouseShapePump is created (in ClientSession) when all channels are

connected. But a VideoControl message can be received before this

happens. If the message has a target_framerate property, it causes a

nullptr-dereference on |mouse_shape_pump_|.



This CL resolves the problem by setting the correct rate, no matter

which order the events occur: creating the pump, or receiving the

target_framerate message.

entry.title: Add autotestPrivate extension API to query base::Feature state
entry.content:
ChromeOS Tast end-to-end tests live in an OS git repository, not in

chromium. The chromium binary can uprev at any time, which can change

the default state of base::Feature flags. This can break Tast tests,

in particular the "informational" ones that don't block uprev.



With this API, Tast tests can update their expectations appropriately

based on the feature state, similar to how it might be done in a

unit test in chromium. Likewise, Tast helper libraries can configure

themselves appropriately (e.g. to work with both an old UI and a new

UI).



This CL uses an allowlist of features based on conversations with

base::FeatureList OWNERS. There is no global list of base::Features,

so there's no way to query the default state of a feature based

solely on a string name.

entry.title: [serial] Allow Bluetooth ports to be requested by service class ID.
entry.content:
Extend the filter parameter for `Serial.requestPort()` and the

response from `SerialPort.getInfo()` to include the Bluetooth

service class ID as per:

https://github.com/WICG/serial/blob/main/EXPLAINER_BLUETOOTH.md



This allows a page to request a Bluetooth service using the

service class ID. Doing so will include that device (if bonded

and detected) in the serial port chooser dialog.



Example port request:



const port = await navigator.serial.requestPort(

{filters: [{bluetoothServiceClassId: 0x1101}]});



Or using the full canonical 128-bit UUID:



const port = await navigator.serial.requestPort(

{filters: [{bluetoothServiceClassId:

"00001101-0000-1000-8000-00805f9b34fb"}]});



and `await port.getInfo()` returns:



{bluetoothServiceClassId: '00001101-0000-1000-8000-00805f9b34fb'}



This is enabled by the `--enable-bluetooth-spp-in-serial-api` flag.



Bug: 1261557,1275643



[serial] Add allowedBluetoothServiceClassIds piping

entry.title: Reland "[QuickStart] Verify the phone's handshake message"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit e6b2fba774f1825fd146ea3955bca28bdc32fb25



The issue was that one of the unit tests was casting an int

into the Version enum to try testing what would happen with an

invalid value. This was a valid test, but proto2 has an assertion

that fails for invalid enum values when is_debug=true.



See Protobuf docs for "void set_foo(Bar value)":

go/proto-generated-cc#enum_field



Original change's description:

> [QuickStart] Verify the phone's handshake message

> verify the AesGcmAuthenticationMessage proto sent by the phone.

>

> See go/cros-quick-start-messaging-specs for more details about this

> handshake protocol.

>

> Note that this does perform parsing on the browser process using

> protobuf. While not as ideal as using Mojo, this is permitted by

> go/rule-of-two.

entry.title: Introduce two checks before creating a SharedDictionaryWriter
entry.content:
Currently CorsURLLoader creates a SharedDictionaryWriter for all CORS

enabled requests when CompressionDictionaryTransportBackend feature is

enabled. (StoragePartitionImpl::InitNetworkContext() sets

shared_dictionary_enabled field of NetworkContextParams, and

NetworkContext creates a SharedDictionaryManager, and

CorsURLLoaderFactory get a SharedDictionaryStorage from the manager, and

CorsURLLoader creates a SharedDictionaryWriter from the storage.)



But the writer should be created when CompressionDictionaryTransport

feature is also enabled. This feature can be enabled in Blink side by

Origin Trial token. So this CL introduces a new flag named

shared_dictionary_writer_enabled in resource request related classes

(network::ResourceRequest, network::mojom::URLRequest and

blink::ResourceRequestHead). blink::FrameFetchContext::PrepareRequest()

sets this flag, and CorsURLLoader checks this flag before creating a

SharedDictionaryWriter.



This CL also introduces a check for is_web_secure_context in

CorsURLLoaderFactory before getting a SharedDictionaryStorage. This is

intended to avoid creating a SharedDictionaryWriter from insecure

context. (Note: Origin Trial feature can't be enabled in insecure

context. But we need this check when we launch this feature after

finishing the Origin Trial experiment.)

entry.title: Add FeatureParam for high memory threshold level in hovercards
entry.content:
With the Round 2 Performance Controls launch we are adding a row

of text at the bottom of the hovercard to communicate how much

memory a tab is currently using. When the number is below the

threshold in the FeatureParam we will render "This tab is using

Y MB". If the number is above the threshold we will render "High

memory usage: X MB".



We want to start with a conservative number and then lower it as

we feel comfortable. Based on initial research from @joenotcharles

and discussions with PM, we are starting with 800 MB.
